07238nam a22008175i 9781580466233DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20042004xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815804662337 a10.1515/97815804662332doi  a(DE-B1597)674433  a(OCoLC)980835412  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a780.90404aThe Pleasure of Modernist Music :bListening, Meaning, Intention, Ideology /ced. by Arved Ashby.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2004] 1bUniversity of Rochester Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b4 b/w, 48 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEastman Studies in Music ;v2900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Reception & Politics -- t1. Intention and Meaning in Modernist Music -- t2. The End of the Mannerist Century -- t3. A Fine Analysis -- t4. In Memory of a Receding Dialectic: The Political Relevance of Autonomy and Formalism in Modernist Musical Aesthetics -- tPart II. Metaphors for Modernism -- t5. Twentieth-Century Tonality, or, Breaking Up Is Hard to Do -- t6. “Tone-Color, Movement, Changing Harmonic Planes”: Cognition, Constraints and Conceptual Blends in Modernist Music -- t7. Sexual and Musical Categories -- t8. Listening to Schizophrenia: The Wozzeck Case -- tPart III. Writing & Listening -- t9. The Musician Writes: For the Eyes of the Deaf? -- t10. “Are You Sure You Can’t Hear It?”: Some Informal Reflections on Simple Information and Listening -- tPart IV. Case Study -- t11. A Fine Madness -- t12. “One Man’s Signal Is Another Man’s Noise”: Personal Encounters with Post-Tonal Music -- tPart V. Belated Modernism -- t13. The “Modernization” of Rock & Roll, 1965–75 -- t14. Refiguring the Modernist Program for Hearing: Steve Reich and George Rochberg -- t15. Modernism Goes to the Movies -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn exploration of the meaning of "modernist" music.The debate over modernist music has continued for almost a century: from Berg's Wozzeck and Webern's Symphony Op.21 to John Cage's renegotiation of musical control, the unusual musical practices of the Velvet Underground, and Stanley Kubrick's use of Ligeti's Lux Aeterna in the epic film 2001. The composers discussed in these pages -- including Bartók, Stockhausen, Bernard Herrmann, Steve Reich, and many others -- are modernists in that they are defined bytheir individualism, whether covert or overt, and share a basic urge toward redesigning musical discourse. The aim of this volume is to negotiate a varied and open middle ground between polemical extremes of reception. The contributors sketch out the possible significance of a repertory that in past discussions has been deemed either meaningless or beyond describable meaning. With an emphasis on recent aesthetics and contexts -- including film music,sexuality, metaphor, and ideas of a listening grammar -- they trace the meanings that such works and composers have held for listeners of different kinds. None of them takes up the usual mandate of "educated listening" to modernist works: the notion that a person can appreciate "difficult" music if given enough time and schooling. Instead the book defines novel but meaningful avenues of significance for modernist music, avenues beyond those deemed appropriate or acceptable by the academy. While some contributors offer new listening strategies, most interpret the listening premise more loosely: as a metaphor for any manner of personal and immediate connection with music. In addition to a previously untranslated article by Pierre Boulez, the volume contains articles (all but one previously unpublished) by twelve distinctive and prominent composers, music critics, and music theorists from America, Europe, Australia, and South Africa: Arved Ashby, Amy Bauer, William Bolcom, Jonathan Bernard, Judy Lochhead, Fred Maus, Andrew Mead, Greg Sandow, Martin Scherzinger, Jeremy Tambling, Richard Toop, and Lloyd Whitesell. Arved Ashbyis Associate Professor of Music at the Ohio State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMusic - 20th century - History and criticism. 4aMusic. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aFilm music.  aIndividualism.  aListening grammar.  aMeaning.  aMetaphor.  aModernist music.  aMusical discourse.  aReception.  aSexuality.1 aAshby, Arved, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAshby, Arved, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBauer, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernard, Jonathan W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolcom, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoulez, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEverett Maus, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLochhead, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLochhead, Judy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaus, Fred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMead, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSandow, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScherzinger, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTambling, Jeremy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aToop, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhitesell, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov